# Portfolio Website

A modern, responsive single-page portfolio website built with HTML, CSS (Tailwind CSS), and JavaScript. This portfolio features interactive persona filtering, project showcases, and a simulated chat interface.

## Features

- **Four Persona Sections**: PM, Consulting, Finance, and Tech with filtered content
- **Interactive Project Showcase**: Modal-based project displays with screenshots
- **Pivots & Adversity Section**: Accordion-style storytelling
- **Beyond the Desk Section**: Personal interests and hobbies
- **Simulated Chat Interface**: Interactive recruiter chat with pre-set questions
- **Responsive Design**: Fully optimized for mobile, tablet, and desktop
- **Modern UI**: Tailwind CSS styling with smooth animations

## File Structure

```
portfolio/
├── index.html          # Main HTML file
├── style.css           # Custom CSS styles
├── script.js           # JavaScript functionality
└── README.md          # This file
```

## Setup Instructions

### 1. Update Personal Information

#### Update Contact Links
Edit `index.html` and replace the placeholder links:

```html
<!-- Find these links in the "Get In Touch" section -->
<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/yourprofile" ...>
<a href="mailto:your.email@example.com" ...>
```

Replace:
- `https://www.linkedin.com/in/yourprofile` with your LinkedIn profile URL
- `your.email@example.com` with your email address

#### Upload Screenshots
The portfolio includes three screenshot placeholders marked with comments:

1. **Pitch Deck Screenshot** - Look for `<!-- SCREENSHOT_PLACEHOLDER_PITCH_DECK -->`
2. **Streamlit App Screenshot** - Look for `<!-- SCREENSHOT_PLACEHOLDER_STREAMLIT_APP -->`
3. **Dashboards Screenshot** - Look for `<!-- SCREENSHOT_PLACEHOLDER_DASHBOARDS -->`

**To upload screenshots:**

1. Create an `images` folder in your portfolio directory:
   ```
   portfolio/
   ├── images/
   │   ├── pitch-deck-screenshot.png
   │   ├── streamlit-app-screenshot.png
   │   └── dashboards-screenshot.png
   ```

2. Replace the placeholder divs with image tags:
   ```html
   <!-- Replace this: -->
   <div class="w-full h-64 bg-gradient-to-br...">
       <p>Upload your screenshot here...</p>
   </div>
   
   <!-- With this: -->
   <div class="screenshot-container">
       <img src="images/pitch-deck-screenshot.png" alt="Pitch Deck Screenshot" loading="lazy">
   </div>
   ```

### 2. Test Locally

1. Open `index.html` in a web browser
2. Test all interactive features:
   - Navigation buttons (PM, Consulting, Finance, Tech)
   - Project showcase modals
   - Accordion sections
   - Chat interface
   - Contact buttons

## Deployment to GitHub Pages

### Method 1: Using GitHub Web Interface

1. **Create a GitHub Repository**
   - Go to [GitHub](https://github.com) and create a new repository
   - Name it `portfolio` or `yourname-portfolio`
   - Make it public (required for free GitHub Pages)

2. **Upload Files**
   - Click "uploading an existing file"
   - Drag and drop all files from your `portfolio` folder:
     - `index.html`
     - `style.css`
     - `script.js`
     - `README.md`
     - `images/` folder (if you've added screenshots)
   - Commit the files

3. **Enable GitHub Pages**
   - Go to your repository settings
   - Scroll to "Pages" section
   - Under "Source", select `main` branch (or `master` if that's your default)
   - Select `/ (root)` folder
   - Click "Save"

4. **Access Your Site**
   - Your site will be available at: `https://yourusername.github.io/portfolio/`
   - It may take a few minutes to go live

### Method 2: Using Git Command Line

1. **Initialize Git Repository**
   ```bash
   cd portfolio
   git init
   git add .
   git commit -m "Initial portfolio commit"
   ```

2. **Create GitHub Repository**
   - Create a new repository on GitHub (don't initialize with README)

3. **Connect and Push**
   ```bash
   git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/portfolio.git
   git branch -M main
   git push -u origin main
   ```

4. **Enable GitHub Pages** (same as Method 1, step 3)

### Method 3: Using GitHub Desktop

1. **Create Repository**
   - Open GitHub Desktop
   - File → New Repository
   - Name it and choose local path
   - Initialize with README (optional)

2. **Add Files**
   - Copy your portfolio files to the repository folder
   - GitHub Desktop will detect changes
   - Write commit message and commit

3. **Publish**
   - Click "Publish repository"
   - Make it public
   - Enable GitHub Pages in repository settings

## Custom Domain (Optional)

To use a custom domain:

1. **Add CNAME File**
   - Create a file named `CNAME` (no extension) in your repository root
   - Add your domain: `yourdomain.com`

2. **Update DNS Settings**
   - In your domain registrar, add a CNAME record:
     - Name: `www` (or `@` for root domain)
     - Value: `yourusername.github.io`

3. **Update GitHub Pages Settings**
   - In repository settings → Pages
   - Add your custom domain

## Troubleshooting

### Images Not Loading
- Check that image paths are correct (relative to `index.html`)
- Ensure images are in the `images/` folder
- Verify file names match exactly (case-sensitive)

### Styles Not Applying
- Ensure `style.css` is in the same directory as `index.html`
- Check browser console for 404 errors
- Verify Tailwind CDN is loading (check network tab)

### GitHub Pages Not Updating
- Wait 5-10 minutes for changes to propagate
- Clear browser cache (Ctrl+F5 or Cmd+Shift+R)
- Check repository settings → Pages for build status

### Chat Interface Not Working
- Ensure `script.js` is loaded (check browser console)
- Verify all JavaScript files are in the correct location

## Browser Support

- Chrome/Edge (latest)
- Firefox (latest)
- Safari (latest)
- Mobile browsers (iOS Safari, Chrome Mobile)

## Performance Tips

1. **Optimize Images**
   - Compress screenshots before uploading
   - Use WebP format for better compression
   - Recommended max width: 1200px

2. **Lazy Loading**
   - Images already use `loading="lazy"` attribute
   - This improves initial page load time

3. **CDN Usage**
   - Tailwind CSS loads from CDN (fast)
   - No additional build step required

## Maintenance

### Updating Content
- Edit `index.html` directly
- Changes will reflect after pushing to GitHub
- GitHub Pages updates automatically

### Adding New Projects
- Add new project cards in the Project Showcase section
- Update `projectData` object in `script.js`
- Add corresponding modal content

